As part of its initiatives in enabling marginalized groups to show their talents and earn income, Hugo Domingo expands its wings on the runway with Lady in Red Fashion by involving disabled fashion designers in the 12th February show. The show that is ushering in the month of love “Valentines Day”, has drawn a lot of local gurus and upcoming fashion designers as well as models. Speaking at the model casting that took place at Elements club Dar es salaam, Mary Fernandez said, after two years organizing the show it has valued the position of  designers with disabilities and decided to give them platforms. She added, there are talented  designers from people with disabilities in Tanzania who need talent’s nourishment and Hugo will forever give them a platform in different ways. Speaking about this year’s event, Mary clarified that,“ This year’s fashion showpiece will be different as a lot of Tanzanians have shown a growing interest in the designing works , many Tanzanians are now aware of what a great platform Lady In Red is for upcoming models and fashion designers as many success stories in the fashion industry  have begun from the runway of Lady is Red Fashion Show” Best Female fashion designer in Africa - Mary Fernandez added: “People should come in large numbers to see the brands designed by local Tanzanians, VIP guests get to enjoy the glamorous night at Serena at a cost of 70,000/- if the customer buys a ticket in advance and buys at the gate will be 100,000 /- while for regular seats it will be 20,000/- if the customer buys a ticket at the gate it will be 30,000/- Commenting on this year's show, Founder Asia Idarous says: “The aim of the platform is to connect Tanzanian designers with the ever-growing market and I urge the government of our beloved President Samia Suluhu Hassan to continue the drive to empower the industry that is currently growing at a fast pace and a lot of Tanzanian designers and models are putting Tanzania on the map in the Global fashion industry. She goes on: “The fact leaders, artists and many other prominent people are now embracing and are being dressed by local Tanzanian designers; this is a sign that the industry is growing and is now more acceptable by the masses”. The goal is to ensure that one day the textile industry contributes significantly to the national income, to have more garment manufacturing industries that can produce in bulk and export, currently many people are employed and self-employed in the industry as designers, models, photographers, designers and other stakeholders who participate in the industry directly or indirectly. The event has drawn big partners in the industry including Ally Rhemtullah, Martina Kadinda, Revolution Events, Black Fox, Hennessy and many more.